<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-12-05T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-12-05T16:00:00-05:00" n="281" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d281">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 Steering Committee/219:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The American Delegate (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="from">Wilson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary
                                    of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-12-05T22:00:00+01:00">December
                                    5, 1932—10 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received December 5—8:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>473. From <persName corresp="#p_DNH1">Davis</persName>. Today <persName corresp="#p_MT1">Matsudaira</persName> gave me the text of the
                            Japanese navy proposal. It is a closely knit plan involving qualitative
                                <pb facs="0529" n="409" xml:id="pg_409"/> restrictions in all
                            categories; quantitative restrictions and consequently ratios in the
                            so-called offensive categories of capital ships, aircraft carriers and
                            heavy cruisers; “uniform tonnage” for five principle powers in defensive
                            categories of light cruisers, destroyers and submarines; and a system of
                            general and special agreements based upon regional grouping. A study of
                            full text is necessary for complete understanding. I presume that you
                            may have been presented with a copy. If not shall I cable full text?
                                [<persName corresp="#p_DNH1">Davis</persName>.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>